recordings.rmk:
No sign of mixed song *Phylloscopus collybita tristis* / *Phylloscopus collybita abietinus* [then probable *Phylloscopus collybita fulvescens* sensu Marova & Leonovich (1993)] as possibly heard here by other observers.

For more information about mixed song in *Phylloscopus collybita tristis* / *Phylloscopus collybita abietinus* (not present here), check out Alula **3** (2008) pp. 108-115, "Mixed song of Chiffchaffs in Northern Russia", Antero Lindholm.

Also interesting is: Ecology and Evolution **7** (7) 2017, pp. 1–12 "Patterns of genetic, phenotypic, and acoustic variation across a chiffchaff (*Phylloscopus collybita abietinus/tristis*) hybrid zone", Daria Shipilina, Maksym Serbyn, Vladimir Ivanitskii, Irina Marova, Niclas Backström

Ireland, Ards and North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk:
This recording is a combination - for comparison's sake - of the typical calls heard from Chiffchaff and Willow Warbler during the breeding season. From the time both species arrive (in late March in Ireland) until young are fledged and start to develop their own vocal powers in July, the voices on this clip are the classic sounds produced by adults.  Calls, especially from Chiffchaffs, are more variable in autumn. No doubt this reflects youthful voices that, if a human analogy was applied, are explained by an adolescent voice maturing - 'breaking', in other words.  But autumn calls are outside the scope of this comment. The clip uses bursts of calling from a Chiffchaff (from 0:01 to the seventh second), then a Willow Warbler (0:10 to the twentieth second), then Chiffchaff (0:22 to the thirtieth second), then Willow Warbler (0:32 to the end). 

Several things are obvious from the clip (and are audible) but other points are best described. Overall, although the utterance from both species is fundamentally a rising note, Chiffchaff's call is loud, far-carrying, abrupt, of shorter duration and monosyllabic.  The quality of the call injects a feeling that the bird is somewhat piqued or curious. In my mind, I see a question-mark at the end of the delivery. 

Willow Warbler's note is softer and, in life, the sound carries a shorter distance. When I made the recordings, I was almost exactly the same distance away from both warblers. Yet the Chiffchaff is clearly louder. This could be a behavioural aspect because, watching migrant Chiffchaffs in autumn, the species calls a lot and is drawn to others. I have not witnessed the same thing in autumn Willow Warblers. Hence, Willow Warbler  calls do not serve the same 'signalling' function. In fact, in autumn, I do not hear much calling from migrant Willow Warblers - less than from Chiffchaffs.  Willow Warbler's call is more 'stretched' than that of Chiffchaff. I checked the call duration of many calls of both species and discovered that Chiffchaff's note lasts just over 0.2 seconds (longest nearer to 0.3 seconds) whereas Willow Warbler's note lasts longer: 0.3 seconds or just over that time. Other qualities that come across in Willow Warbler's diction include a more mellow feel and, in terms of delivery, a 'slower' start that suggests an intake of breath as the bird 'builds the note'. In Chiffchaff, the call is, as it were, fully formed in an instant.

recordings.loc: Ireland, Ards and North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk: Song from a Chiffchaff that was agitated by my presence. I assume that its nest was nearby. When a Chiffchaff is agitated, it incorporates 'titter notes' between song phrases. You can hear these on the clip too. I have to say that, listening to many Chiffchaffs, I seldom hear one that lives up to its English name and alternates 'chiff' with 'chaff' - in the manner of a Cuckoo. But this individual comes close!

recordings.file-name: XC562501-CHIFFCHAFF MASTER MP3 OF CALLS (Mar, May, April).mp3
recordings.rmk:
This is a set of calls from three different recordings (the last clip actually contains calls from a pair of Chiffchaffs).  To compare these Chiffchaff calls with the equivalent calls from Willow Warbler, click here: XC560316.

The calls are all from the spring (recorded in March, April and May). After listening to calls of autumn Chiffchaffs,  I feel that there is a minor difference in the quality of the sound. Spring calls have more 'oomph' and are less 'innocent' than calls I hear in autumn.  By way of a crude demonstration, I actually thought that the middle set of calls in the clip (recorded on 25 May 2020)  came from a Chaffinch!  The loudness and emphatic quality initially wrong-footed me. I would not expect that to happen in autumn, when a Chiffchaff's calls always strike me as plaintive and coming from a small warbler, although they are not feeble - and can be quite strident, especially from a freshly-arrived migrant on migration.

recordings.rmk:
THIS RECORDING HAS BEEN REPLACED BY A BETTER ONE! The new version is XC562501.

I apologize for adding more than one individual Chiffchaff in this clip. The sounds are calls from four different Chiffchaffs (one clip has calls from two birds - a breeding pair) during the early part of the breeding season. Short silences separate each clip. These occur at 0:04, 0:17 and 0:34. My reason for doing this is because I wish to use the comparison of several birds on a Facebook post about distinguishing the voice - and appearance - of Chiffchaff from Willow Warbler.  Therefore, I have uploaded a similar clip of two different Willow Warblers under that species here: XC560316. The Chiffchaff clip comes from Ireland. The first two excerpts are from County Down in late March and early April; the final cut is from Inishbofin, Co. Galway, in late October. In fact, the last Chiffchaff clip (from 0:34) is already uploaded on to xeno-canto.  The bird in this clip (XC507107) was calling on 25th October and its voice was recorded remotely by hiding the recorder among its favourite feeding habitat.

Bird at close range calling from trees on edge of orchard. This is a typical sounding bird amongst the many wintering in the UAE. The subspecific identify of the wintering birds here is not clear; although many- like this one -  sound at least superficially rather close to tristis on call, the vast majority when singing do not sound like tristis, instead having a song (very) close to that typically heard in NW European birds. This bird was not heard singing. Comments on the subspecific identification are most welcome.

Noise filtered at 2kHz. Light woodland and scrub flanking river. Call resembles tristis but slightly less 'flat'. On the basis of genetic studies, Rakovic et al. (2019) inferred that Chiffchaffs across the Elborz mountains of Iran were attributable to menzbieri but the precise boundary between menzbieri and caucasicus remains to be firmly established. For details see http://deanar.org.uk/general/articles/IranChiffchaffs.htm.

Classic calls from an autumn migrant. The bird was feeding among alders and willows in a sheltered corner behind a graveyard wall. The habitat also contained ivy flowers that attracted numerous flies. Sounds like Nirvana for a migrant Chiffchaff!  The recorder was secreted in a cavity in the graveyard wall, facing some ivy blooms. The bird was not calling very much at all - and quite softly too - but over the course of two hours it produced sufficient sound to put together this clip. The opening few seconds record the bird flying to perch close to the recorder. In the distance, a Blackbird flies off and gives a short salvo of alarm just after 0:13.

Presumed "mixed" pair. One of the birds is a sweeoo-caller, the other one a normal-caller. Sweeoo-caller circles around me, comes pretty close (< 3 metres), alarms right into my face, while the second bird keeps in the background. I guess I must be close to their nest site to trigger such an alarm. After recording: When I move on, the calls fade off, and one of the birds (which one?) starts singing.
